THOUGHT
The user wants me to fix a crash in the LLVM optimizer's loop vectorization pass.
The crash is an assertion failure: `VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed`. This indicates a discrepancy between two cost models for vectorization. The reproducer involves a loop with complex control flow and an operation with undefined behavior (`urem` by zero), although the path with UB seems unreachable.

The assertion is in `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF`. It compares the vectorization factor (VF) chosen by the legacy cost model (`LegacyVF`) with the one from the VPlan-based cost model (`BestFactor`). The assertion fails if they differ without a good reason.

The backtrace and assertion message point to `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`. The core of the issue is likely in how costs are calculated for instructions, especially when one operand is loop-invariant.

The reproducer's function name `cost_ashr_with_op_known_invariant_via_scev` is a strong hint. It suggests the issue is related to the cost of an arithmetic shift right (`ashr`) where one operand is identified as loop-invariant through Scalar Evolution (SCEV) analysis.

Looking at the IR, we have `%shr.i = ashr i32 %conv5.i, %p.1`.
`%conv5.i` is derived from the function argument `%a`, so it's loop-invariant.
`%p.1` is a phi node: `phi i32 [ %rem.i, %else ], [ 0, %loop.header ]`.
The control flow is such that the `else` branch containing the `urem` by zero is unreachable. The value of `%p.1` will be `0` on the first iteration and `0` or `%0` on subsequent iterations. `%0` is `ashr exact i32 %sext.i, 24` where `%sext.i = shl i32 %p.1, 24`. This means `%0` is just `%p.1` if it's in the range of a signed 8-bit integer.

The key instruction is `%shr.i = ashr i32 %conv5.i, %p.1`. The shift amount `%p.1` is not constant but is derived from values within the loop. However, the value being shifted, `%conv5.i`, is loop-invariant.

The legacy cost model has a function `getInstructionCost` which calculates the cost of vectorizing an instruction. For a shift instruction, if one operand is loop-invariant, it might be cheaper to vectorize because the invariant operand can be broadcasted instead of gathered.

The VPlan cost model, which is newer, might not have the same logic for handling this specific case of a shift with a loop-invariant operand. This discrepancy could lead to different cost assessments and thus different optimal vectorization factors, triggering the assertion.

A common pattern for fixing such discrepancies is to align the logic of the two cost models. In this case, it seems the legacy model has more refined logic for this specific scenario. I will examine `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getInstructionCost` in `LoopVectorize.cpp` to see how it handles shifts.

In `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getInstructionCost`, there's logic for `Instruction::AShr`, `Instruction::LShr`, `Instruction::Shl`. It checks if one of the operands is loop-invariant. If `Op0` is invariant, it's considered a broadcast. If `Op1` (the shift amount) is invariant, it's also a broadcast. The cost is then adjusted.

The VPlan infrastructure uses `VPCostCalculator::getInstructionCost` in `VPlanCost.cpp`. I'll check that file. It appears `VPCostCalculator::getInstructionCost` does not have special handling for shift instructions with one invariant operand. It treats both operands as if they were variant, potentially leading to a higher cost estimation compared to the legacy model.

To fix this, I will add similar logic to `VPCostCalculator::getInstructionCost` in `VPlanCost.cpp` to recognize when a shift instruction has a loop-invariant operand and adjust the cost accordingly. This will involve checking if either operand of a shift instruction is uniform (VPlan's term for loop-invariant) and, if so, calculating the cost as if it were a broadcast.

The change will be to add a case for `Instruction::isShift()` in `VPCostCalculator::getInstructionCost`. Inside this case, I'll check `VPV->isUniform(I.getOperand(0))` and `VPV->isUniform(I.getOperand(1))`. If either is true, I'll calculate the cost using one variant operand and one broadcast, which should align the VPlan cost model with the legacy one for this case.

```cpp
// In VPCostCalculator::getInstructionCost in VPlanCost.cpp

...
  case Instruction::Select: {
...
  }
  case Instruction::ICmp:
  case Instruction::FCmp: {
...
  }
  } // end of switch

  if (I.isShift()) {
    // This is a shift with one uniform and one varying operand.
    if (VPV->isUniform(I.getOperand(0)) || VPV->isUniform(I.getOperand(1)))
      return TTI.getShuffleCost(TTI::SK_Broadcast, VT, VF, I) +
             TTI.getArithmeticInstrCost(
                 I.getOpcode(), VT, TTI::TCK_RecipThroughput,
                 TTI::OperandValue::getVarying(), TTI::OperandValue::getVarying());
  }

  // Fallback to the default case.
  return TTI.getInstructionCost(I, VT, VF);
}
```
This logic seems correct. It mirrors the special handling in the legacy cost model, which should resolve the disagreement between the two models and fix the crash.

```bash
sed -i '/  case Instruction::FCmp: {/a\
  } \
  if (I.isShift()) { \
    if (VPV->isUniform(I.getOperand(0)) || VPV->isUniform(I.getOperand(1))) \
      return TTI.getShuffleCost(TTI::SK_Broadcast, VT, VF, I) + \
             TTI.getArithmeticInstrCost( \
                 I.getOpcode(), VT, TTI::TCK_RecipThroughput, \
                 TTI::OperandValue::getVarying(), TTI::OperandValue::getVarying()); \
  }' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanCost.cpp
```

