The current logic for binary ops is:
`return Ctx.TTI.getArithmeticInstrCost(getOpcode(), ResTy, Ctx.CostKind);`

This doesn't account for uniform operands. The legacy cost model, in `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getInstructionCost`, has this logic:
```cpp
  if (I->isShift()) {
    // This is a shift with one uniform and one varying operand.
    if (isUniform(I->getOperand(0)) || isUniform(I->getOperand(1)))
